,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old (gravida 0) woman presents to the Emergency Department with a six hour history of rapid onset left-sided abdominal pain. Her last menstrual period was six weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and the oral contraceptive pill is her only regular medication. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn initial examination, her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure is 100/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Repeat observations 30 minutes later show a blood pressure of 95/50 mmHg and pulse 115/min. There is tenderness in the left iliac fossa. A speculum examination shows blood from the cervix and the serum quantitative beta-hCG is 5500 mIU/ml. Her complete blood examination and biochemistry are normal. A transvaginal ultrasound shows an empty uterus, distension of the left fallopian tube and a small amount of free fluid in the pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dilation and curettage","Laparoscopy","CT scan and review","Intravenous fluid replacement and review","Methotrexate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is potentially unstable and likely has an ectopic pregnancy. The definitive management involves urgent\u003Cstrong\u003E laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E and removal of the ectopic tissue to decrease the risk of rupture and control bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient needs more than \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluid replacement and review \u003C/strong\u003Eas the fall in her blood pressure over such a short period of time indicates likely haemodynamic instability and ongoing intra-abdominal bleeding from an ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerforming a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not going to add any further information and is very unlikely to influence the management decision that active surgical intervention is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst medical management with\u003Cstrong\u003E methotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in selected patients who are haemodynamically stable and amenable to close follow-up, it would not be appropriate in this patient. In addition, the effectiveness of methotrexate sharply declines with higher levels of bHCG (88% at\u00a04000mIU/mL). Patients would need to be aware of the risks of potential medication toxicity, the need for routine monitoring and the ongoing risk of rupture which may require urgent surgery at a later date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilatation and curettage\u003C/strong\u003E, on the background of an ultrasound reporting an empty uterus will be unlikely to yield any tissue and carries a risk of infection, uterine perforation and Asherman\u2019s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An ectopic pregnancy in a haemodynamically unstable patient demands prompt surgical intervention."],"references":["Department for Health and Wellbeing, Government of South Australia. South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline: Bleeding \u0026 pain in early pregnancy \u2013 ectopic pregnancy, miscarriage \u0026 PUL. 2019 Oct. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/clinical+resources/clinical+programs+and+practice+guidelines/perinatal+practice+guidelines/bleeding+and+pain+in+early+pregnancy+ectopic+pregnancy+miscarriage+and+pul","Elson CJ, Salim R, Potdar N, Chetty M, Ross JA, Kirk EJ, et al. Diagnosis and management of ectopic pregnancy. BJOG. 2016;123(S1):e15\u2013e55. doi: 10.1111/1471-0528.14189. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1111/1471-0528.14189"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90202"}},